chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Laws on abortion should aim to protect human dignity in all its forms—taking developing life seriously while ensuring no one is denied timely, medically appropriate care. A balanced framework can preserve access in the earlier stages of pregnancy, set narrowly tailored limits later that track medical realities like viability, and include explicit exceptions for rape, incest, and serious threats to life or major bodily health, written so clinicians can act without legal fear. Enforcement should focus on safety, informed consent, and preventing coercion rather than criminalizing patients or good-faith medical practice. Common ground is stronger when these rules are paired with measures that reduce unplanned pregnancies and support families—contraception and education, prenatal and postpartum care, adoption support, and practical help for parents.
